  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "In the age of curated social media news feeds, & large media conglomerates, how does one find and read the suppressed journalism?",
  "response": "Finding and reading suppressed journalism in an era dominated by curated social media and large media corporations can be challenging, but there are several strategies you can employ to discover more independent and less mainstream sources of information:\n\n1. **Alternative News Websites**: Look for independent news outlets that prioritize investigative journalism. Websites such as ProPublica, The Intercept, Democracy Now!, and Common Dreams often provide in-depth reporting and analysis on issues that mainstream media may overlook.\n\n2. **Follow Journalists and Independent Reporters**: Many journalists operate independently or work with smaller platforms. Following them on social media or subscribing to their newsletters can give you access to their work. Look for journalists known for covering underreported topics.\n\n3. **Utilize News Aggregators**: Platforms like Feedly or Flipboard allow you to curate your own news streams. You can add sources that align with your interests in independent journalism and suppressive issues.\n\n4. **Explore Academic Journals and Research**: Academic publications can offer in-depth analyses of topics that mainstream media may not cover. Websites like Google Scholar or JSTOR provide access to a wealth of research articles.\n\n5. **Engage with Nonprofit and Advocacy Organizations**: Many nonprofits and NGOs focus on specific issues (e.g., human rights, environmental concerns, freedom of the press) and publish reports and investigative pieces that contribute to a broader understanding of complex topics. Look for organizations that align with your interests.\n\n6. **Listen to Podcasts**: Many independent journalists and commentators produce podcasts that explore issues in more depth than traditional news formats. Searching for podcasts on specific topics can lead you to insightful discussions and analyses.\n\n7. **Use Social Media Wisely**: Instead of relying solely on algorithms, actively seek out specific hashtags, follow independent voices, and join groups or forums that focus on critical journalism. Twitter, Reddit, and other platforms can be valuable for finding engaged communities.\n\n8. **Check Local Journalism**: Local news outlets may cover stories that national or international media ignore. Discover independent or community-based journalism platforms in your area.\n\n9. **Investigative Journalism Networks**: Organizations like the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists (ICIJ) or the Center for Investigative Reporting provide access to collaborative investigations that may not hit mainstream channels.\n\n10. **Be Critical of Source Credibility**: When you come across articles or reports, assess the credibility of the sources. Look for work that is fact-checked, well-researched, and transparent about its sources and funding.\n\nBy diversifying your media consumption and actively seeking out less mainstream sources, you can access a more comprehensive view of global events and issues often overlooked by traditional media.",
